Processor features are now tied to what motherboard you purchased: the processor checks and disables them if you didn't pay enough.
Intel does this with overclocking: even with a K-processor, you can't fiddle with the multiplier unless you have a Z motherboard.
AMD does it with PCI Express: even though it's the CPU that generates high-speed PCIe lanes, the chipset isn't involved, and the motherboard's sole involvement is providing 40 pairs of wires, AMD processors will disable their PCIe 4.0/5.0 support if you didn't pay for at least a B550.

Anyways, what you should do is find someone who assembled a PC that they're happy with, and copy that. Or buy one from a local store.

I might as well spoonfeed you about Cookie as a whole.
Those characters are from the famous Cookie subculture. It's a series of memes that was born out of a failed Touhou fan voice drama, titled Marisa and Alice’s Cookie Kiss, uploaded in 2010 featuring eight amateur voice actresses and over twenty artists.
Due to its terrible quality, frequently switching art styles, and the poor skills of the voice actors, the drama became a meme on the Japanese internet and subsequently got "invaded" by the Manatsu no Yo no Inmu fanbase, who actually appreciated the cheesy storytelling and spun off the original voice drama.
And because of the many inside jokes and Inmu references, Cookie is considered a subculture independent from Touhou. Though, its notoriety came from its association with cyberharassment and doxxing of the voice actors who participated in the dramas.
Fans typically refer to a character of the Cookie series by an initialism of the voice actor's name, commonly UDK for Uzuki and SNNN for Sananana.

Back to your question, the NYN and ICG characters first appeared in Kussoo (https://youtu.be/TRyt69ipONM), one of Cookie's many iterations, and the source of countless clips and inspired otoMADs.

About C, look at variables, conditionals, loops, funcions, arrays, structs, pointers, and some data structures: arrays, dynamic arrays, linked lists, trees, hash tables, binary trees. and the usual functions to manipulate them: insert, search/lookup, delete, iteration.

Also about compilers, start with how arithmetic expressions can be interpreted. Infix to postfix conversion (shunting yard algorithm for example), and the postfix stack calculator to evaluate those postfix expression.
